    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="162"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72112/286½a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        President <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 26, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose for your perusal an
                    article which appears in the pro-German publication, <hi rend="italic">The
                        Fatherland</hi>, of October 28, 1914.<note n="9" xml:id="d162fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> It is called forth by the recent public statement in regard
                    to “Neutrality and Trade in Contraband,” which you will recall was approved by
                    you before being issued (copy enclosed).<note n="10" xml:id="d162fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1914Supp#pg_573">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1914, supp., p.
                        573</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
